body:
Right, but it seemed odd that the previous issue remained closed.

I think the resize handler is actually [this](https://github.com/ipython/ipython/blob/b09f7cf936e6397dd02d27a27a6f9668aeb8db7a/IPython/html/static/base/js/page.js):

```
Page.prototype._resize_site = function() {
        // Update the site's size.
        $('div#site').height(window.innerHeight - $('#header').height());
     };
```

which is used here:

```
Page.prototype.bind_events = function () {
        // resize site on:
        // - window resize
        // - header change
        // - page load
        var _handle_resize = $.proxy(this._resize_site, this);

        $(window).resize(_handle_resize);

        // On document ready, resize codemirror.
        $(document).ready(_handle_resize);
        events.on('resize-header.Page', _handle_resize);
    };
```

If that is the thing @jdfreder was describing, I don't think it is needed. It is much better to use responsive design for everything.

I think now I understand what is the purpose of the resize handler. It is changing the height of the `#site` element to obtain the effect of a sticky header. I commented the `_resize_site` method in `/IPython/html/static/base/js/page.js`:

```
 Page.prototype._resize_site = function() {
     // Update the site's size.
     //$('div#site').height(window.innerHeight - $('#header').height());
      };
```

and then I added `position: fixed;` and `width: 100%` to the `#header` in `/IPython/html/static/style/style.min.css`:

```
 #header {
   /* Initially hidden to prevent FLOUC */
   display: none;
   background-color: #ffffff;
   /* Display over codemirror */
   position: fixed;
   width: 100%;
   z-index: 100;
  }
```

and included a `top-margin` in `#site` and a couple of media queries to keep the margin between `#header` and `#site`:

```
#site {
  width: 100%;
  display: none;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  -moz-box-sizing: border-box;
  -webkit-box-sizing: border-box;
  overflow: auto;
  margin-top: 9em;
}

@media screen and (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio:0) and (max-width: 636px) {
      #site {
          margin-top: 11em;
        }
    }

@media (max-width: 633px) {
    @-moz-document url-prefix() {
        #site {
            margin-top: 11em;
        }
    }
}
```

The first media query targets webkit browsers and the second targets Firefox. In this particular case, Firefox and Chrome seem to measure width differently. However, in general, this shouldn't be the case. As a workaround, I had to use two media queries. I tested in Chrome 41.0.2272.76 and Firefox 36 on Ubuntu and works okay. Maybe this can be helpful to fix the original issue.

There is an issue in the /tree page because now the `#site` element has a larger margin. However, this should be easily fixed adding an additional rule for that page.

**UPDATE**.

Correction: Chrome and Firefox measure widths differently: [Firefox versus webkit measurements for media queries based on width](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/8977605/firefox-versus-webkit-measurements-for-media-queries-based-on-width)
